04742nam a22005175i 9780773576599DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735765997 a10.1515/97807735765992doi  a(DE-B1597)655201  a(OCoLC)760072439  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE92bM36 2009eb 7aLAW1100002bisacsh04a346.71304/32089971 aMcNab, David T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Place for Fairness :bIndigenous Land Rights and Policy in the Bear Island Case and Beyond /cDavid T. McNab. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v5900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tMeeting Places and Negotiations, 1763–1850s -- tFirst Nations and the British “Civilization” Policy in the Early Nineteenth Century -- tStories of Teme-Augama Anishnabai Land Rights and the Robinson Huron Treaty of 1850 and Its Aftermath -- t“Don’t fix it”: Reflections on Ontario Aboriginal Policy and Processes, 1976–1984 -- tThe Bear Island Trial, the Steele Judgement, and the First Settlement Offer, 1982–1986 -- tBear Island and Land Rights Under a Liberal Majority, 1986 –1988 -- tThe Temagami Blockade of 1988 -- tThe 1989 Blockades and the 1990 Treaty of Co-Existence -- tOka and the Blockades in Northern Ontario, Summer 1990 -- tReflections since the 1990s -- tRetrospect: Towards a Place for Fairness -- tAcronyms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAboriginal policy and claims negotiation in Canada is seen to be a murky and perplexing world that has become an important public issue and has significant policy implications for government spending. Aboriginal land policy in Canada began as an Aboriginal initiative. In No Place for Fairness, David McNab - a long time advisor on land and treaty rights for both government and First Nations groups - looks at the Bear Island Indigenous rights case, initiated by the Teme-Augama Anishinabe, to explore why governments fail to deal effectively with Aboriginal land claims. The book, divided into two sections, includes a survey of the historical background of the Bear Island claim followed by a more personal series of reflections about what happened as the claim encountered decades of policy hurdles, court cases, public protests, and above all resistance by the Temagami First Nation. McNab provides details of how ministers and their senior officials resisted real efforts to resolve problems as well as examples of field staff resisting government attempts at resolution. He also shows that government entities such as the Indian Commission of Ontario and the Native Affairs Directorate were largely used as "mailboxes" where successive federal and provincial governments sent things they wanted to bury. No Place for Fairness is the story of what happens when Aboriginal peoples' political rights are crammed into the Euro-Canadian legal system. McNab makes a clear case that a legalistic approach to these problems is wholly inadequate and that more important things - like fairness - must be recognized as paramount if a just and lasting Aboriginal land policy is to be created.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357659940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773576599423Cover